    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_11_07_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>  
                        <date when="1813-11-07">Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 7<hi rend="superscript">h.</hi> 1813</date></dateline></opener><note>98</note>
                
                <p>
                   
                    I congratulate you my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">friend</persName><lb/>
                    with all my heart upon <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrouH1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. B's</persName> being better than his <add>word</add><lb/>
                    -Send me the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Edinb2">Edinburgh Review</title><lb/>
                    as soon as you can <add>by post</add> under <choice><orig>co-<lb/>
                    ver</orig><reg>cover</reg></choice> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LittE2">Sir E. B. Littlehales Bar<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</persName><lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin-Castle_IE">Dublin Castle</placeName> - It is sometimes<lb/>
                    three weeks in coming to us by<lb/>
                    the usual mode.- I rejoice<lb/>
                    that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrouH1">Brougham</persName> has executed<lb/>
                    his article and long to see<lb/>
                    it - As I am naturally <choice><orig>coward<lb/>
                    ly,</orig><reg>cowardly</reg></choice> I feel much relieved by<lb/>
                    finding, that I shall, at all<lb/>
                    events, have the advantage<lb/>
                    of seeing another go through<lb/>
                    a perilous trial before me.<lb/>
                    - As to the rest, as my sole<lb/>
                    wish is to do what may be<lb/>
                    useful to an excellent book,<lb/>
                    &amp; advantageous, or agreeable<lb/>
                    to a still more excellent<lb/>
                    friend, I shall be governed<lb/>
                    entirely by the consideration<lb/>
                    of what will best secure these<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_11_07_page02.jpg"/>
                    objects - When we see the review<lb/>
                    I think that my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> and I -<lb/>
                    putting our literary vanity<lb/>
                    quite out of the question shall<lb/>
                    be able to judge impartially <del><choice><orig>whe<lb/>
                    ther</orig><reg>whether</reg></choice> we could add any thing</del><lb/>
                    -whether any thing new remains<lb/>
                    to be said, in another review<lb/>
                    - whether any material parts<lb/>
                    of the work have been omitted<lb/>
                    - or whether any erroneous<lb/>
                    view of the subject has been<lb/>
                    given to the public.<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    You will at the same<lb/>
                    time form your own opinion;<lb/>
                    &amp; your more intimate <choice><orig>know-<lb/>
                    ledge</orig><reg>knowledge</reg></choice> of all the general &amp; <choice><orig>par-<lb/>
                    ticular</orig><reg>particular</reg></choice> <hi rend="underline">bearings</hi> of the subject,<lb/>
                    &amp; proportional <add>importance</add> of the different<lb/>
                    parts of the work, will enable<lb/>
                    you to form a more perfect<lb/>
                    judgment than we could,<lb/>
                    as to what is best to be done<lb/>
                    - or left undone in future -<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_11_07_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>99</note>
                    - I have such entire <choice><orig>depen-<lb/>
                    -dance</orig><reg>dependence</reg></choice> upon your integrity,<lb/>
                    &amp; belief in your knowledge<lb/>
                    of my character, that I have<lb/>
                    no fear, that compliment,<lb/>
                    or what is sometimes <add>erroneously</add>called<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">delicacy</hi>, should prevent you<lb/>
                    from saying exactly, &amp; fully<lb/>
                    what you really think, &amp; wish -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    On the one hand, there<lb/>
                    is no danger of my being <choice><orig>dis-<lb/>
                    -couraged</orig><reg>discouraged</reg></choice> by any <hi rend="underline">anticipation,</hi><lb/>
                    that merely takes from me<lb/>
                    the gloss, or glory of novelty, or<lb/>
                    any imaginable portion<lb/>
                    of literary fame - as the review<lb/>
                    would, I trust, not be known<lb/>
                    to be ours all this is out of<lb/>
                    the question -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    On the other hand - you<lb/>
                    would not, I am sure, do us<lb/>
                    the injustice to let us go on<lb/>
                    <del>with</del> <add>under</add> the belief that we could<lb/>
                    serve you, if in your own<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_11_07_page04.jpg"/>
                    conscience you see little <choice><orig>pro-<lb/>
                    bability</orig><reg>probability</reg></choice> of our effecting our<lb/>
                    purpose -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> is not at home, &amp;<lb/>
                    I write this note merely to<lb/>
                    hasten your sending the <choice><orig>re-<lb/>
                    view,</orig><reg>review</reg></choice> which I know he will<lb/>
                    be as impatient as I am to see<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I will delay saying more<lb/>
                    till his return - only I <hi rend="underline">must</hi><lb/>
                    thank you for all the kindness<lb/>
                    &amp; all the entertainment of<lb/>
                    your letter. Adieu -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    We see in the newspapers the loss<lb/>
                    of the <hi rend="underline">Lauristinus</hi> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GrahT1">Captain Graham</persName><lb/>
                    - I hope this <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GrahT1">Captain Graham</persName> is not<lb/>
                    the husband of the M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Graham<lb/>
                    whom we liked so much?- Pray tell<lb/>
                    us - we are very anxious to know.<lb/></p>
                
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
